    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nCalling `take` on a reversed iterator (`vim.iter`) is not respected. If `take` is called before `rev`, then it will be respected. If the iterator is unreversed (`iter:rev():rev()`) then `take` will also again be respected.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```lua\r\nvim.iter({ 1, 2, 3 }):take(2)\r\n-- GOOD: Produces { 1, 2 }\r\n\r\nvim.iter({ 1, 2, 3 }):rev():rev():take(2)\r\n-- GOOD: Produces { 1, 2 }\r\n\r\nvim.iter({ 1, 2, 3 }):take(2):rev()\r\n-- GOOD: Produces { 3, 2 }\r\n\r\nvim.iter({ 1, 2, 3 }):rev():take(2)\r\n-- PROBLEM: Produces { 3, 2, 1 }\r\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n```lua\r\nvim.iter({ 1, 2, 3 }):rev():take(2)\r\n-- EXPECTED: { 3, 2 }\r\n```\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.10.0-dev-2671+gdc110cba3\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nN/A\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nbob",
